Analyze output of countingAlleles¶

Written by Thuy N. Nguyen on 11/11/19. Edited on 03/09/2020 to include motivations for each part of the analysis and visualization of the data.¶

A summary of my data analysis journey:

  • Selection experiment lab notebook reference: TN11p57
  • Sample library preparation lab notebook reference: TN11p71-81
  • GeneWiz HiSeq run quality control: "191009 genewiz ngs qc". And run summary: "191031_hiseqRun_counts"
  • Merged overlapping paired-end reads with USEARCH. See README in 191025_miseqData_genewiz in bioHPC:
  • Analyzed these reads with countingAlleles.py
  • BioHPC path: "lamella.biohpc.swmededu/project/greencenter/ReynoldsLab/s157382/191025_miseqData_genewiz"

The goals of this script are:

  1. to evaluate the raw allele counts of each DHFR mutant in the saturation mutagenesis library in both the WT and R166Q TYMS backgrounds.
  2. to sanity check fits of growth rate effects for a subset of mutants with known biochemical activities
  3. to calculate and fit growth rate for all mutants in this first replicate of the DHFR libraries.

    outfile = open(f,'r').readlines()
    for l in outfile[0:3]: 
        sp_l = l.strip().split('\t')
        if sp_l[0] == 'read_total:':

        if sp_l[0] == 'read_pass:':
            pass_reads.append(float(sp_l[1]))
    open(f,'r').close()

# each sub-library gets a list of all possible amino acid mutations
mutants_lists = {}
for sl_id in sublibraries:
    mutants_lists[sl_id] = []
    mutants_lists[sl_id].append('WT')

    wtseq = wt_aa_sequence[sl_id]
    for posix,pos in enumerate(aa_pos[sl_id]):
        wt = wtseq[posix]+str(pos)
        for a in AA:
            mutants_lists[sl_id].append(wt+a)

Organizing and storing data in two forms:¶

  1. a matrix of DHFR sequence vs amino acids for each sub-library, timepoint, and tyms background. This is to easily do matrix based math and visualization of heat maps.
  2. a dictionary of mutant (key) and mutant count (values) to keep track of names of mutants associated with each mutant count.

NOTE: This is not ideal. You should try to later edit this code so that you are not so restricted to using two separate data types in your analysis of allele counts.

countRaw_mut_mat = np.zeros(shape = (len(sublibraries),len(time),len(tyms),len(wt_aa_sequence['sl1']),len(AA)))
countRaw_WT_mat = np.zeros(shape = (len(sublibraries),len(time),len(tyms)))
countRaw_dict = {}

countPresent_mut_mat = np.zeros(shape = (len(sublibraries),len(time),len(tyms),len(wt_aa_sequence['sl1']),len(AA)))
countPresent_WT_mat =  np.zeros(shape = (len(sublibraries),len(time),len(tyms)))
countPresent_dict = {}

fitness_mut_mat = np.ones(shape = (len(sublibraries),len(tyms),len(wt_aa_sequence['sl1']),len(AA)))
fitness_dict = {}

for s in sublibraries:
    fitness_dict[s] = {}
    countPresent_dict[s] = {}
    countRaw_dict[s] = {}
    for t in tyms:
        fitness_dict[s][t] = {}
        countPresent_dict[s][t] = {}
        countRaw_dict[s][t] ={}
        for tp in timeName:
            fitness_dict[s][t][tp] = []
            countPresent_dict[s][t][tp] = []
            countRaw_dict[s][t][tp] = []
            
def fill_data():
    if mutID in mutants_lists[sl_id]: #fill dictionaries 
        #count_threshold = round(mutCount/100)
        countRaw_dict[sl_id][tymsID][tp].append(mutCount)
        if mutCount >= count_threshold:
            countPresent_dict[sl_id][tymsID][tp].append(mutCount)
        else: 
            countPresent_dict[sl_id][tymsID][tp].append(1) #set to 1 so that absent mutants are log10(1) == 0. 

        if mutID == 'WT':  #now fill matricies
            countRaw_WT_mat[sublib_ix,tp_ix,ts_ix] = mutCount            
            if mutCount >= count_threshold:
                countPresent_WT_mat[sublib_ix,tp_ix,ts_ix] = mutCount#- count_threshold
        else:
            mut_ix = list(aa_pos[sl_id]).index(int(mutID[1:-1]))
            aa_ix = AA.index(mutID[-1])
            countRaw_mut_mat[sublib_ix,tp_ix,ts_ix,mut_ix,aa_ix] = mutCount
            if mutCount >= count_threshold:
                countPresent_mut_mat[sublib_ix,tp_ix,ts_ix,mut_ix,aa_ix] = mutCount #- count_threshold

for f in outname: 
    countsFile = open(f,'r')
    countsFileRead = countsFile.readlines()
    
    samp_id = f.strip().split('/')[-1].strip('.txt') #this is specific to the format of your output file names
    
    sampleSL, tp, tymsID = sampleInfo[samp_id].split('_') #sub-library ID, timepoint, or tymsID

    tp_ix = timeName.index(tp)
    ts_ix = tyms.index(tymsID)
    #print tp,tymsID
    
    #account for samples with mixed sub-libraries
    sampleSL_list = list(sampleSL.split(','))
    if sampleSL_list == ['mix']:
        sampleSL_list = ['sl1','sl2','sl3','sl4']
    
    for l in countsFileRead[6:]: #only pulling out information after stats like total read counts and failed read counts
        sp_l = l.strip().split('\t')

        mutID = sp_l[1]
        mutCount = float(sp_l[2])
        
        sl_id = sp_l[0] #this mutant has this sub-library associated with it
        if sl_id in sampleSL_list: #check to see if you expected to see it in the sample you prepared
            sublib_ix = sublibraries.index(sl_id)
            fill_data()

    countsFile.close()

    ##plots a heatmap of log10(matrix)
    ##matrix - the data
    ##color map default is viridis, you can change it to whatever you want
    ##x and y ticks spacing defaults to len of x and y axes of matrix
    ##x and y tick labels default to the indicies of x and y axes of the matrix. change it if you want to..

    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 10,20

    yticks=np.arange(len(matrix[:,0]))
    ylabel = dhfr_wt_seq#np.arange(len(matrix[:,0]))
    
    xticks = np.arange(len(matrix[0,:]))
    xlabel= AA#np.arange(len(matrix[0,:]))
    
    plt.imshow(np.log10(matrix), cmap = colormap, vmin = MIN, vmax = MAX,interpolation = 'nearest')
    
    plt.colorbar(shrink = 0.3, orientation = 'vertical', pad = 0.01)
    plt.xticks(xticks+0.5,xlabel)
    plt.yticks(yticks+0.5,ylabel)
    plt.grid(color = 'k',linestyle = '-',linewidth = 2)

What are the growth rate effects of DHFR mutants with known catalytic activities?¶

In [83]:
def filterCounts(mutCounts, time = [0,4,8,12,20,24]):
    tp2fit = [0]
    counts2fit =[0]
    mutCounts = np.array(mutCounts)
    ixnonzeros = np.array(mutCounts) != 0 #step 2 determine where present timepoints are 
    if len(mutCounts[ixnonzeros]) >= 3:
        t = np.array(time)
        tp2fit = t[ixnonzeros]
        counts2fit = mutCounts[ixnonzeros]
        if mutCounts[-1] == 0:
            counts2fit = np.append(mutCounts[ixnonzeros],1) #replace zero with one
            tp2fit = np.append(tp2fit, t[-1])
    return tp2fit, counts2fit

def relFreqFunc(mutCounts, WTcounts):
    tp2fit, counts2fit = filterCounts(mutCounts)
    
    
    #if not present at the beginning of the experiment, continue 
    if 0 not in list(tp2fit):
        relFreq = []
        tp2fit = [] #retrun a blank list if not present at the beginning of the experiment 
        
    if 0 in list(tp2fit):
        relFreq = []
        for tpix, tp in enumerate(tp2fit):
            wt = WTcounts[tpix]
            wt0 = WTcounts[list(tp2fit).index(0)]
            mut = counts2fit[tpix]
            mut0 = counts2fit[list(tp2fit).index(0)]
            relFreq.append(np.log2(mut/wt)-np.log2(mut0/wt0))
    
    return tp2fit, relFreq

    kcat_temp =float(dhfr_kinetics['kcat'][ix])
    km_temp = float(dhfr_kinetics['km'][ix])

    velocity_tmp = np.divide(kcat_temp*dhf,km_temp+dhf)
    velocity[dhfr.lower()] = velocity_tmp

cl_mutants = ['WT','M42F','L54I','W22H','D27N','L28F','L28Y','F31V','F31Y','G121V','T113V']
countPresent_cl_mat = np.zeros(shape = (len(cl_mutants),len(timeName),len(tyms)))
relFreq_cl_mat = np.zeros(shape = (len(cl_mutants),len(timeName),len(tyms)))
fitness_cl_mat = np.zeros(shape = (len(cl_mutants),len(tyms)))
for mutix, mut in enumerate(cl_mutants):
    if mut == 'WT':
        continue
    mutPos_aa = AA.index(mut[-1])
    for sl_ix, s in enumerate(sublibraries):
        dhfrN = int(mut[1:-1])
        if dhfrN in list(aa_pos[s]):

                for tsix, ts in enumerate(tyms):
                    countPresent_cl_mat[mutix,tpix,tsix] = \
                    countPresent_mut_mat[sl_ix,tpix,tsix,mutPos_dhfr,mutPos_aa]

#calculate relative frequencies and fitness for full library
relFreqFilter_mutNames = [],[] 
relFreqFilter_timepoints = [],[]
relFreqFilter_ft = [],[]
relFreqFilter_fitsError = [],[]

listofFitnessEffects = [],[]

fitTally = 0

for tsix, ts in enumerate(tyms):
    for slix, slid in enumerate(sublibraries):
        for aaix, aa in enumerate(AA):
            for posix, pos in enumerate(aa_pos[slid]):
                mutName = wt_aa_sequence[slid][posix] + str(pos) + aa
                relFreqFilter_mutNames[tsix].append(mutName)
                
                mutMat = countPresent_mut_mat[slix,1:,tsix,posix,aaix]
                wtMat = countPresent_WT_mat[slix,1:,tsix]
                tp2fit, relFreq = relFreqFunc(mutMat,wtMat)
                if mutName[0] == mutName[-1]:
                    fitness_mut_mat[slix,tsix,posix,aaix] = 0
                                                            #shoving 0 in WT positions 
                                                            # so that they show up as white pixels
                                                            # in the fitness heatmap
                    continue
                    
                if 0 in tp2fit: #each mutant MUST BE PRESENT AT THE BEGINNING OF THE EXPERIMENT
                    
                    
                    relFreqFilter_timepoints[tsix].append(tp2fit)
                    relFreqFilter_ft[tsix].append(relFreq)

                    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(tp2fit,relFreq)
                    fitness_mut_mat[slix,tsix,posix,aaix] = slope
                    rsquared = r_value**2

                    if slope != np.log10(-1):
                        fitTally+=1
                    
                    relFreqFilter_fitsError[tsix].append([slope,intercept,rsquared])
                    listofFitnessEffects[tsix].append(slope)
                else: #if they are not present shove in a NAN in the matrix 
                    fitness_mut_mat[slix,tsix,posix,aaix] = np.log2(-1)

##plots a heatmap of log10(matrix)
##matrix - the data

##x and y ticks spacing defaults to len of x and y axes of matrix

    yticks=np.arange(len(matrix[:,0]))

    #plt.colorbar(shrink = 0.3, orientation = 'vertical', pad = 0.01)

In conclusion, R166Q TYMS broadly rescues growth rates of DHFR mutants in the WT TYMS background.

What to do next?

  1. collect two more replicate measurements to determine error threshold for each DHFR mutant effect on bacterial growth rate
  2. use average and error growth rates to test phenomenological model that relates DHFR and TYMS biochemical function to effect on growth rates.
  3. calculate epistasis and map positions in DHFR enriched for buffering and aggravating epistasis on the strucutre of the enzyme.
  4. determine if epistasis is correlated to evolutionary positional conservation
